description._value: This study evaluates changes in metabolite levels in hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) cases vs patients with liver cirrhosis by analysis of human blood plasma using gas chromatography coupled with mass spectrometry (GC-MS). Untargeted metabolomic analysis of plasma samples from participants recruited in Egypt was performed using two GC-MS platforms: a GC coupled to single quadruple mass spectrometer (GC-qMS) and a GC coupled to a time-of-flight mass spectrometer (GC-TOFMS). Analytes that showed statistically significant changes in ion intensities were selected using ANOVA models. These analytes and other candidates selected from related studies were further evaluated by targeted analysis in plasma samples from the same participants as in the untargeted metabolomic analysis. The targeted analysis was performed using the GC-qMS in selected ion monitoring (SIM) mode. The method confirmed the significance of ten analytes as candidate biomarkers for HCC in patients with liver cirrhosis. These include metabolites previously reported to have significant association with HCC including glutamic acid, valine, and leucine as well as newly discovered candidates such as alpha tocophereol, lactic acid, alpha-D-glucosamine 1-phosphate, citric acid, sorbose, and tagatose. Our findings indicate up-regulation of metabolites involved in branched-chain amino acid (BCAA) pathways. Increase or decrease in BCAA levels, is regulated by a fast response from enzymatic system. BCAAs have been reported to have significant role in many types of cancer leading to their use as a supplement for treatment in several cases.

title._value: GC-MS based plasma metabolomics for HCC biomarker discovery in Egyptian cohort

description._value: Adult patients were recruited from the outpatient clinics and inpatient wards of the Tanta University Hospital in Tanta, Egypt. The participants consist of a total of 89 subjects (40 HCC cases and 49 patients with liver cirrhosis). The protocol of the study was approved by the ethical committee at Tanta University. Detailed characteristics of the patient populations are provided in Table 1. Through peripheral venepuncture, single blood sample was drawn into 10 mL BD Vacutainer sterile vacuum tubes without the presence of anticoagulant. The blood was immediately centrifuged at 1000g for 10 min at room temperature. The serum supernatant was carefully collected and centrifuged at 2500g for 10 min at room temperature. After aliquoting, serum was kept frozen at -80 °C until use. Primary tubes and serum aliquots were labeled using anonymous confidential code numbers with no personal identifiers. Identification codes were cross-referenced with clinical information in a pass code protected computer system.

Plasma metabolites were extracted by adding 1 mL of working solution composed of acetonitrile, isopropanol, and water (3:3:2) containing isotope-labeled internal standards at a concentration of 1.25 μg/mL (tyrosine-3,3-d2, glutamic acid-2,3,3,4,4-d5, alanine-2,3,3,3-d4, phenylalanine-phenyl-d5-2,3,3,-d3, glycine-d5, myristic acid d27) to 30 μL of plasma. After vortexing, samples were centrifuged at 14,500 rpm for 15 min at room temperature. The supernatant was then divided into two, 460 μL each, for analysis by the two GC-MS systems. The supernatants were then concentrated to dryness in speedvac. The dried samples were kept at -20 °C until derivatization prior to analysis by GC-MS.</br>
The dried samples were derivatized in each batch prior to injection following previously designed steps using trimethylsilyl (TMS).28, 29 Briefly, 20 μL of a 20 mg/mL methoxyamine hydrochloride in pyridine was added to the dried extracts, vortexed and incubated at 80 °C for 20 minutes. After returning the samples at room temperature, 91 μL of MSTFA + RIs was added, vortexed and incubated at 80 °C for 20 minutes. Samples were then centrifuged at 14,500 rpm for 15 minutes, and 60 μL of the supernatant was transferred into 250 μL clear glass autosampler vials.

For the GC-qMS, Agilent J&W DB-5MS column (30m × 0.25mm × 0.25μm film 95% dimethyl/ 5% diphenyl polysiloxane) + 10m Duragard Capillary column was installed and calibrated. Prior to sample analysis, the GC system was locked by performing retention time locking (RTL) of myristic acid d27 to 16.75min. The samples were injected in splitless mode, with the injection port held at 250 °C. The initial oven temperature was held at 60 °C for 1 minute and then ramped at 10 °C/min to 325 °C and held for 10 minutes. The post run is 1 minute to allow the oven cool down to 60 °C. </br>
For the GC-TOFMS system, Agilent HP-5 column (30m x 0.32mm i.d. x 0.25μm film 95% dimethyl 5% diphenyl polysiloxane) was used.  99.9% pure Helium (Roberts Oxygen) was set at a constant flow of 1.5mL/min. The oven temperature was held constant at 70 °C for 4 minutes and then ramped at 20 °C/min to 300 °C at which it was held constant for 5 minutes. The transfer line temperature between the GC and the MS was set to 225 °C. Electron impact ionization at 70eV was employed with an ion source temperature of 200 °C.

The GC-qMS data were acquired in 37.5 minutes with 5.9 minute solvent delay at normal scan rate with the mass range 50-600. MSD transfer line was held at 290 °C, ion source 250 °C and the mass analyzer at 150 °C. </br>
For GC-TOFMS, after 5 minutes of solvent delay, filament number 1 was turned on and mass spectra were acquired over the range of m/z of 50-600 at an acquisition rate of 20 scans per second. The detector was operated in the range of 1400 to 1600V with an optimized voltage offset of 200V. Recording ended after 19.5 minutes.

For GC-qMS and GC-SIM-MS, .D Agilent files were converted to netCDF format using ChemStation software. For GC-TOFMS, peg LECO files were converted to netCDF format using ChromaTOF software.</br>
All intensities obtained from processing tools were log-transformed to be used with ANOVA models.

Putative metabolite identifications were determined based on spectral matching using the Fiehn and NIST libraries. To reduce the false discovery rate in identification process, we extracted all TMS compounds from NIST library (around 5,000 compounds with more than 22,000 spectra). This was not necessary for the Fiehn library, as it includes spectra only from TMS compounds.

RI standard mixture was spiked into each sample analyzed by GC- TOFMS. The standard was prepared by mixing a series of fatty acid methyl esters (FAMEs) with a series of alkanes. Specifically, FAMEs, including C8, C9, C10, C12, C14, C16, C18, C20, C22, C24, C26, C28 and C30 linear chain length were dissolved in chloroform at a concentrations of 0.8mg/mL (C8-C16) and 0.4mg/ml (C18-C30). 100 μL of each FAME standard was mixed together and 1.2mL of chloroform was added for a final volume of 2.5mL (FAME-2). Alkanes were purchased as a mixture of long chain Alkane standards, containing all 16 evenly-numbered n-alkanes from C10 to C40, at a concentration of 50mg/L in n-heptane each. Alkane mixture was mixed with FAME-2 at a ratio of 1:4, vortexed prior to spiking it into each sample. For the samples analyzed by GC-qMS, the RI standard mixture consisted of only FAMEs.
The blank samples were prepared together with the samples by adding the derivatization agent to an empty eppendorf tube and following the same steps.  The QC sample in each batch was prepared by pooling 5 μL of each derivatized sample within the batch. In both cases, 60 μL of the mixed reaction mixture was transferred into 250 μL clear glass autosampler vials with low-volume inserts and cap.

title._value: GC-MS based plasma metabolomics for HCC biomarker discovery in Egyptian cohort
